post_text:
Notice:

THE GREEN BAY SCHOOL AND ADMINISTRATIVE CENTER WILL BE CLOSED FRIDAY, AUGUST 21, 2020 - ANY MEETINGS SCHEDULED FOR IN PERSON AT GREEN BAY ARE CANCELLED.

The facilities department will direct a deep cleaning of the Green Bay / Administrative Offices building per the COVID-19 cleaning protocols.

A staff member at Green Bay School/Administration Center building tested positive for COVID-19 today, on August 20. The staff member is now in isolation at home.

The staff member has been in contact with the Lake County Health Department. Our COVID-19 Team has also been in contact with the Lake County Health Department staff. The Lake County Health Department Contact Tracing department staff will work with the staff member so any close contacts will be identified and contacted for notification. If you do not receive communication from the Lake County Health Department directly, you have not been identified as a close contact.

post_text:
New podcast episode from the superintendent - Back To School: LISTEN HERE: https://anchor.fm/michael-lubelfeld/episodes/Back-to-School-Update-Aug-9---D112-ehtdgs

North Shore School District 112 is preparing to return students and staff to school on September 3 in a Hybrid learning model. This model calls for significant risk mitigation with respect to the COVID-19 Global Pandemic. Students and staff have not been on site since March 12 - it's time for schooling to restart - in as safe a manner as possible. With enhanced air quality investments, cleaning and sanitizing investments, PPE investments, curricular material investments, and much, much, more, the Board and administration remain committed to public safety as they bring back a version of in-person schooling with an enhanced set of distance or "e" learning as well. This is a back to school update from the superintendent of schools. Learn more at https://www.nssd112.org/domain/1243 LISTEN HERE: https://anchor.fm/michael-lubelfeld/episodes/Back-to-School-Update-Aug-9---D112-ehtdgs

City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
June 23 at 6:00 AM ·

Remember to follow social distancing guidelines and be courteous in outdoor spaces! As you enjoy time outdoors, please follow these guidelines from the National Recreation and Park Association, as well as all new public health guidelines implemented by the facility you are visiting. Information about Park District of Highland Park parks and facilities is regularly updated at pdhp.org.

Guidance from the Illinois Department of Public Health (IDPH) is clear that face coverings can help prevent the spread of illness. Please remember to wear a face covering when a six-foot distance from others cannot be maintained, even when outside. As a reminder, face coverings are required in public indoor spaces, according to the Restore Illinois Phase 3 guidelines.

More COVID-19 information can be found at www.cityhpil.com/covid-19.

Lake County Health Department and Community Health Center is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
June 19 at 10:17 AM ·

PRESS RELEASE: Lake County officials warn residents about contact tracing scams where criminals pretend to be contact tracers to steal vital information like social security numbers and banking information.

A contact tracer will never:

- Ask for your Social Security number;
- Ask for money, bank account or credit card numbers, or any other form of payment;
- Ask for your immigration status; or
- Threaten consequences of not participating or answering questions.

Read more: https://bit.ly/37HvQtM

City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
June 19 at 6:00 AM ·

On Friday, June 25, the Baha'i Community of Highland Park will host a community conversation about racial and social justice. The Zoom event will feature a keynote speech from Dr. Joy DeGruy, an internationally renowned researcher, educator, and well-known author on race.

Dr. DeGruy's remarks will be followed by a panel discussion and Q&A with local thought leaders from North Shore interfaith, inter-cultural, and government circles. Highland Park Chief of Police Lou Jogmen will join Mirah Anti, Director of Equity at Highland Park/Deerfield High Schools, Lauren Bondy, LCSW, clinical social work/therapist, and Rabbi Wendi Geffen of North Shore Congregation Israel. Participants may register via Zoom via the link or the QR code in the photo below.

City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
May 15 at 11:00 AM ·

We celebrate Firefighters in May on International Firefighters Day, a time to recognize and honor the sacrifices that firefighters make to ensure that our communities and environment are as safe as possible. It is also a day in which current and past firefighters can be thanked for their service and dedication.

This year, our first responders are working harder than ever to protect public health and safety. Thank you to everyone in the Highland Park Fire Department for your service!

post_text:
As you may have heard or read, today Governor Pritzker announced that all schools in Illinois will remain closed, and he announced the suspension of in-person learning for the remainder of the school year. For us, that means that June 4, 2020, will reflect the end of the school year 2019-2020.

We recognize that this development will raise questions about the impact on students, staff, and families for the remainder of this school year with respect to learning, emotional concerns, end of year traditions, and more. We know this news is tough for many reasons. Let’s all reflect on our own personal health and our families. We will get through this difficult time together. Read more at https://bit.ly/3clQQaC

City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
April 16 at 9:00 AM ·

Join Highland Park High School in celebrating this year's seniors by participating in in the nationwide #BeTheLight Challenge!

This Friday, April 17 at 8:20 p.m. (20:20 military time) HPHS will be turning on the stadium lights at Wolters Field for 20 minutes to honor and recognize the Class of 2020.

HPHS students, families, staff, and all Highland Park residents are welcome to join in by turning on your porch lights or another light outside your home. Then, help spread the light by sharing your photos to social media with the hashtag: #GiantsBeTheLight

While we all want to be together, please abide by social distancing rules and do not congregate at the school. Pictures from the stadium and school will be posted on Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.

Let’s flood our streets and social media with light that represents our love, support, and admiration of the Class of 2020!

City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
April 16 at 6:00 AM ·

On Wednesday, April 15, Mayor Nancy Rotering and City Manager Ghida Neukirch hosted a virtual meeting of government partners serving the Highland Park area. Leaders from the governmental entities in attendance each shared information about their organization's response to the COVID-19 pandemic. The City of Highland Park and partners are committed to working collaboratively to serve the community during this unprecedented challenge.

Joining Wednesday's meeting were Lake County Commissioner Paul Frank; Highland Park Public Library President Rich Basofin and Executive Director Jane Conway; North Shore Water Reclamation District Commissioner Rhoda Pierce, Director Brian Dorn, and Deputy Director David Miller; Moraine Township Supervisor Anne Bassi; Park District of Highland Park President Brian Kaplan and Executive Director Brian Romes; North Shore School District 112 President Bennett Lasko and Superintendent Mike Lubelfeld; and Township High School District 113 Superintendent Bruce Law.

post_text: Sharing a message from Highland Park Mayor Rotering!
shared_text:
City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
April 9 at 5:00 PM ·

Keeping Our Community Safe & Informed: A Message from Mayor Rotering

"I think we can all agree that the past few weeks have been trying, and the weeks and months ahead are filled with uncertainty. Life will be uncomfortable and difficult. We are fighting for our lives while simultaneously experiencing a faltering economy. We are working to adjust to our new normal, the message of staying home is sinking in, and we continue to see stories about how we are stepping up to help each other and lift spirits."

Read the Mayor's full remarks at https://cityhpil.com/news_detail_T21_R610.php.

Mayor Rotering delivered these remarks at the virtual City Council meeting on Monday, April 6, 2020. The meeting was livestreamed on Facebook and HPTV, and the video is available on the City's website.

EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY, AND UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE ALL SCHOOLS IN NORTH SHORE SCHOOL DISTRICT 112 ARE CLOSED.

To safeguard the health and wellness of students, staff, and the community, I have made the decision to close all schools in North Shore School District 112 effective immediately. This includes students who attend special education schools outside of District 112 schools.

There will be no classes tomorrow Friday, March 13; our projected return date is Tuesday, April 14 (this reflects a two week period following spring break and anticipated travel from our community). This is a dynamic situation and the return to school date may change. Read more: https://bit.ly/2TOh9Qy

post_text: Special Board of Education Meeting - March 12th, 2020
text: Special Board of Education Meeting - March 12th, 2020

post_text:
As you know, we have been monitoring the quickly evolving situation regarding the COVID-19 Pandemic. At this time, it is our plan that all schools in North Shore School District 112 will be in session through Thursday, March 19, 2020. After consulting with the superintendents of Districts 106, 109, and 113, we are staying in close contact with decisions such as these and their impact on the community.

In order to mitigate the risk of exposure of COVID-19 to our students while schools remain open, the District is taking preventative action by postponing or canceling all non-essential after school events, including athletic competitions, musicals, grade level-sings, that gather large groups of visitors into our school buildings now (March 12th) through March 27th, effective immediately. We are also canceling all outside facility rentals between March 12 and March 27 as well. Read more at https://bit.ly/2vRSgKD

This video debuted during the presentation and encapsulates each of our building leader's answer to "WHY" they do what they do every day for our staff and students. Watch at: https://youtu.be/KIt9xKoDOO4 #112Leads!

YOUTUBE.COM
Portrait of a Principal

post_text: Nominations are due March 9 at noon for the Highland Park Awards!
shared_text:
City of Highland Park, Illinois - Government
March 4 at 5:00 PM ·

Nominations are due March 9 at noon for the Highland Park Awards!

Categories include the Arts Award, Environmental Award, Humanitarian Award, and the Robert Barnard Character Counts Awards. All awards recognize outstanding achievements in, or contributions to, the community in their respective category.

The Highland Park Awards Ceremony will be held on Wednesday, April 22 at 7 PM, in the Highland Park High School Auditorium; each award recipient, their family and friends, and the community at large, are invited to attend.

To learn more about the Awards or to submit a nomination, visit www.cityhpil.com/awards. For more information, please contact the City Manager’s Office at 847.926.1000

post_text: Tonight the NSSD112 Board of Education approved the hiring of Ms. Niki Scofield as Teaching & Learning Coordinator and Mr. Jeremy Wickham as Coordinator of Information Technology effective July 1, 2020. Mr. Wickham currently serves as Associate Principal of Oak Terrace School in NSSD112 and Ms. Scofield currently serves as Principal of Gavin School in District 37. Read more at https://bit.ly/2TjMslI

post_text: Highland Park Police Chief Lou Jogmen, the HP Police Department, and the Art Center Highland Park teamed up with Edgewood Middle School Creative Media Arts (CMA) classes to showcase twenty-two students selected to exhibit one of their projects from CMA. The Project, called PhotoVoice was created to engage students to focus on wellness, health, and positive choices.
shared_text:
Edgewood Middle School
February 6 at 8:56 PM ·

A BIG Thank you to our AMAZING CMA STUDENT ARTISTS, the Highland Park Police Department, Chief Lou Jogmen, Officer Amanda Duchak and Officer Pawel Geneja. Thank you to the Art Center HP, Caren Rudman and James Lynch for showcasing our students' work in their Gallery. Exhibit will be up until February 24, 2020. Open to the Public. text:
Highland Park Police Chief Lou Jogmen, the HP Police Department, and the Art Center Highland Park teamed up with Edgewood Middle School Creative Media Arts (CMA) classes to showcase twenty-two students selected to exhibit one of their projects from CMA. The Project, called PhotoVoice was created to engage students to focus on wellness, health, and positive choices.
